author: bors-libra
body:
:exclamation: Invalid command
Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |

author: bors-libra
body:
:exclamation: Invalid command
Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |

author: modocache
body:
Nice report, thanks @lxfind! I brought this up in #9550 as well. One immediate cause is that the restricted visibility error that should cause the error message you're expecting is currently being treated as a "non-blocking" error. This allows execution of the compiler to continue to bytecode generation and, without this struct type resolved, it panics. Another issue is that diagnostics are printed at the end of execution, so if the compiler panics, diagnostics are not printed -- that's why you see only the stack trace here, and no error messages.

One fix could be, as in #9550, to revert this error back to a "blocking" error that would prevent the compiler from continuing its execution and panicking. IMHO another improvement would be to install something like a signal handler that prints any queued up diagnostics if the compiler crashes.

(And, FWIW, part of my plan for next year is to add automated tests for these Move book examples, so we can make sure they continue working as documented.)

author: zmanian
body:
I notice that state snapshots are incrementally verifiable.

We implemented an instant sync feature in Tendermint recently that combines a light client for verified commits without running the transactions and incrementally verifiable snapshots.

https://github.com/tendermint/tendermint/blob/master/docs/architecture/adr-042-state-sync.md

Seems like the proposed back up strategy heads in that direction.

author: bmwill
body:
Looks great! Once we get the double quoting thing fixed we can get this merged.

Couple things/questions:
- Looks like you'll need to rebase on the latest tip of main, this is my fault as I was moving some stuff around and moved the logger crate from the `common` directory to the `crates` directory. Should hopefully be a straight forward rebase 🤞🏼 
- At first glance this looks like it only supports recording the span data when invoking a tracing log macro and not when the diem log macros are used. Is that correct? Ideally we'd be able to get the span data in both cases but that can be done at a later point in time (or maybe by then tracing will support valuable)

author: bors-libra
body:
:exclamation: Invalid command
Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |

author: modocache
body:
I discussed this with @tnowacki yesterday evening and we came up with what I think are a few good ideas:

* We both liked @vgao1996's proposed `branch`, `branch_true`, `branch_false` statements (and I think we all agree not to include `if (cond) b0 else b1;` syntax, which isn't representable in a single bytecode instruction), but the names we settled on were `jump`, `jump_if`, and `jump_if_false`. In the future we can change the bytecode mnemonics to match. (I personally don't mind `branch` vs `jump`, but what I do want is for the Move IR syntax to match the bytecode mnemonics.)
* For label syntax, we decided that always requiring labels, and always requiring that blocks be terminated with a "terminator" instruction, would be a nice property for Move IR, especially for CFG analysis. And, instead of having the first block in a function definition be a special case, we thought that requiring the label always be specified would be a good way to go. Here's an example:
  ```
  foo() {
    let x: u64;   // Local declarations appear before any labels.
    let y: &u64;  // In the future we may change the `let ... : ...;` syntax to instead be
                  // `locals:` followed by a sequence of identifier/type pairs such as `x: u64;`.
  label b0:
    return; // The sequence of statements in b0 must end with a terminator such as `return`.
  }
  ```

I'll update this PR with code to match this approach.

body:
Thanks for the review! 👍 

> Just a note: changes in devsetup seem not to trigger the prover tests right now in CI. To manually test whether our .Net dependency boogie works, can you verify that (a) devsetup.sh -y works (b) cd language/move-prover; MVP_TEST_FEATURE=default cargo test.

That being said, I'll also run the tests locally now as per your suggestion (I've confirmed that `dev_setup.sh -y` works on an M1 macOS machine, I'll also double-check on Intel). Also, I believe AWS is having some difficulties right now that are impacting our CI, so I may not land this until later.

author: phlip9
body: @CapCap Looks like there's a flaky test in stream-rpc, seems timeout related? you might consider using a time simulator like `common/time-service` (https://github.com/diem/diem/blob/main/common/time-service/src/lib.rs)

author: CapCap
body: @phlip9 this is a weird one that I haven't been able to replicate locally after running it many many times; this call should never take more than a few ms, and the data should be there as soon as the FN is started: if it times out at 500ms it's very unlikely that waiting logger would have changed anything :-(

author: phlip9
body:
yeah CI is a good exercise for timeouts : )

we'll get super contended VMs or other expensive tests (like smoke-test) running at the same time, causing your test to get stalled for a while. i've had luck getting flaky test failures to surface by running like 50 of the same test in like 50 terminal windows lmao

for example, i have a bash alias

```bash
function retry() {
    while "$@"; do :; done
}
```

and i just run 50 instances of `RUST_BACKTRACE=1 retry cargo test -p diem-json-rpc -- test_websocket_requests`. sometimes it can take a few hours if the issue is rare.

of course, a more systematic approach would be to carefully control all non-determinism like timeouts, concurrency, IO, etc... but this definitely gets tricky when using a dependency like warp : (  iirc there's a warp::test thing to exercise your filters, but i haven't tried it yet haha

Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |

author: bob-wilson
body: I don't think anyone has been paying much attention to keeping the README files updated. We should definitely fix this. We should also decide to either (1) keep these updated, or (2) pare them back to minimal info that is less likely to become outdated.

author: levensti
body: @bob-wilson and @MaxMohammadi: I've gone ahead and fixed the broken link. I figured it'd be a good patch for now even if the team ends up shortening the README later.

author: bob-wilson
body: The `stdlib/modules` link is still broken, and regardless this README really needs some bigger updates.

author: bob-wilson
body: For the first part, wouldn't it be better to put the description as a comment in errmap.rs instead of a README file?

author: modocache
body: It looks like this was resolved in #9752, so I'll close this issue. Nice work! 👍

author: bob-wilson
body: We had some debate about this awhile ago and it was never clear that there was a consensus to add u16 and u32. I can see the argument for having them for the sake of uniformity and completeness, but on the other hand, these will incrementally add to the size of the VM and the matrix of operations that we need to test. It's good to have an issue tracking this, but we should have more discussion before anyone starts implementing these.

author: jolestar
body: Should we also consider u256? make it easier to interact with eth Solidity and Move?

author: sblackshear
body:
>  It's good to have an issue tracking this, but we should have more discussion before anyone starts implementing these.

Totally agree. I filed this (but neglected to explain) because I recently encountered a use-case use-case for `u32`: compatibility with the BCS vector type. BCS defines the vector length as a `u32`, so if you are trying to replace (e.g.) a `Option<T>` field with a `NewT` in a layout-compatible way, you want to do `struct NewT { _len: u32, t: T }`. 

This is (of course) a breaking change, but there are cases where it useful to do something like this. The thing I wanted to do was generalize the [`guid: vector<8>`](https://github.com/diem/diem/blob/main/language/move-stdlib/modules/Event.move#L28) we use in `Event` to a `GUID` type that can be used in contexts outside of `Event`. To do this without breaking old `EventHandle`'s, we can replace the `guid` field with `GUIDWrapper { _len: u32, g: GUID }`.

author: sblackshear
body:
> Should we also consider u256? make it easier to interact with eth Solidity and Move?

This is also worth considering--do you have examples in Starcoin code where this would be useful?

author: jolestar
body:
> > Should we also consider u256? make it easier to interact with eth Solidity and Move?
> 
> This is also worth considering--do you have examples in Starcoin code where this would be useful?

We use u128 to represent the token value in starcoin, but Ethereum uses u256 in the token. When we try to mirror the ERC20 token to starcoin,  need to calculate it as u256.

author: modocache
tnowacki
body:
Thanks for the question!

In Move, there are two key code units: Modules and Scripts. 

Modules represent reusable code stored on chain, and Scripts are the "main" functions used to define a given transaction. We believe that this model more closely resembles classical programming that developers are used to (a bunch of existing libraries + custom code + a main function). We also hope that this paradigm proves more flexible and reusable than the contract model of Ethereum (you can encode singleton contracts in a Module)

That being said, we do expect a lot of scripts to just be a single function call to some public function in a Model. 
As a developer feature, we plan on adding a Move source language function annotation that will generate a script wrapper. 
But! Keep in mind that you can put any code you want in a script! This can help build new interactions between modules without having to publish another new module. 

---

Additional details:
- Modules are code units published and stored on chain. 
  - Unlike in Ethereum, they are not singleton contracts. They do not have any "contract" data tied to them directly. They behave much more like modules you might be used to in other languages, such as Java, O'Caml, or Rust
  - For the data or state of the "contract", resources are the non-copyable structs stored in accounts. Resources are defined by a module and all access control over them is defined by the functionality exposed by that module
- Scripts represent a transient function/block of code that is not stored on chain
  - The scripts can then invoke any public function in modules stored on chain. 
  - Think of these scripts like the `main` function for an program in a language like C

author: aihuawu
body:
If I understand it correctly, the block chain with accounts is something like a sql database. the module is the deployed
sql procedure. the script is external sql statements.

I am still not sure if I should build a thin script/fat module application or the other way around.
Do you have some suggestion on this?

Thanks.

george wu

author: sblackshear
body: The way we tend to do things is to design for thin scripts/fat modules. This makes common operations convenient and cheap, but gives clients flexibility to write "fatter" scripts for use-cases the application/module designer didn't/couldn't anticipate.

author: jolestar
body: @aihuawu  if you want to directly call a function by name and argument like Ethereum, you can write a tool to generate script by module and function names and arguments. It's really convenient for manual testing a module function.

author: tnowacki
body:
> The way we tend to do things is to design for thin scripts/fat modules. This makes common operations convenient and cheap, but gives clients flexibility to write "fatter" scripts for use-cases the application/module designer didn't/couldn't anticipate.

I would add that this tends to only really occur currently because our modules define new types, i.e. structs and resources. We then write fat modules over those types that handle all sorts of things that might need to be done in a script or another module. 
But publishing modules on-chain will have some sort of storage cost. This is likely higher than the cost of sending a "fatter" script over the wire. So if you are only interacting with existing types and modules, you probably don't need to publish another module; a script would do just fine.

author: JoshLind
body: Silly question: what's the migration plan here? e.g., if we rip this code out, are we making the assumption that we'll never push to environments that already have encrypted addresses again? Or are we going to work some magic to handle already encrypted addresses?

author: gregnazario
body:
> Silly question: what's the migration plan here? e.g., if we rip this code out, are we making the assumption that we'll never push to environments that already have encrypted addresses again? Or are we going to work some magic to handle already encrypted addresses?

We're making the assumption we'll not use the encrypted addresses again.  If we use this code we'll need to do genesis again, since nodes could use the original validator set to try to find validators.  The other option is do a write set to decrypt all the addresses, and then update all validators.

author: tnowacki
sblackshear
body: My use-case is fairly mundane: I have a system that keys transactions by their hash, and some transaction types include modules.

author: tnowacki
body: Wouldn't it be best to just hash the original `Vec<u8>` before the `CompiledModule` was deserialized? Feels a bit more robust than hashing the Rust representation

author: sblackshear
body: Fair point--let me manually implement a `Hash` that does this instead.

author: tzakian
body:
One worry that I have with implementing `Hash` for the module is that (as far as I'm aware) the `Hash` trait is agnostic to the hasher used, and because of this there aren't any guarantees around hash collisions. This could then lead to potential footguns if someone isn't careful when getting the hash of the module. 

I like hashing the serialized representation, but I would prefer even more fixing the hash that could be used for `CompiledModule`s to something that we know is OK (e.g., Sha256), but I'm not sure if that's possible....But this is probably what we'll do for producing compiled-module checksums for publishing.

author: sblackshear
body:
> One worry that I have with implementing Hash for the module is that (as far as I'm aware) the Hash trait is agnostic to the hasher used, and because of this there aren't any guarantees around hash collisions. This could then lead to potential footguns if someone isn't careful when getting the hash of the module.

I think this is true of anything in Rust that implements the `Hash` trait. `CompiledModule` can't anticipate what kind of hash its clients will be looking for, and shouldn't try to--its role is only to defines an API for piping the bytes into the hash computation.

author: tnowacki
body: Just to wrap this up. One thing you could do is something like `HashableCompiledModule { bytes: Vec<u8>, module: CompiledModule> }` and then manually implement `Hash` to skip the module field?

author: vgao1996
body:
> However, current trait interface cannot make the adapter aware the current package to test.

Would you mind sharing a more detailed example/use case with us? Without the details, this feels like an anti-pattern to me. My intuition is that if you need different behaviors for different packages/entry points, then you should implement different adapters for them. Or is it that you are trying to read some additional configs from the test directory?

author: lerencao
body:
> > However, current trait interface cannot make the adapter aware the current package to test.
> 
> Would you mind sharing a more detailed example/use case with us? Without the details, this feels like an anti-pattern to me. My intuition is that if you need different behaviors for different packages/entry points, then you should implement different adapters for them. Or is it that you are trying to read some additional configs from the test directory?

I'd like to:
- compile all modules in the package system and add it into state before transactional test case run, so that we can use  modules of the package directly in test file.
- read named address mapping defined in package's `Move.toml`.
- read additional configs located in package root directory, like you said.

All the cases need that the `MoveTestAdapter` can find the current package path.
As far as I can see, current design of adapter trait deals with tasks defined in test files, and has no way to get the location of test files, as it's not designed to be used in package systems.

author: vgao1996
body:
@tnowacki Looks like I went through the tests a bit too fast and misclassified a few of them. Will get them restored/rewritten. My apologies and thank you so much for catching this!!!
- `transactions/tx_assoc.mvir`
- `modules/publish_resource_internal.mvir`, `modules/has_resource_internal.mvir`, `modules/get_resource_internal_bypass.mvir`
- `cant_borrow_field_of_resource.mvir`

I still think these should be deleted:
- `publish/publish_two_modules.mvir`, 
  - Already ported to `move-vm/transactional-tests/tests/module_publishing/publish_two_modules.mvir`
- `publish_module_and_use.mvir`
  - Already ported to `move-vm/transactional-tests/tests/module_publishing/publish_module_and_use.mvir`
- `natives/vector/vector_module.mvir`
  - Already ported to `move-vm/transactional-tests/tests/native_functions/vector_module.mvir`
- `mutation/mint_money.mvir `
  - What this intends to test is covered by `cant_borrow_field_of_resource.mvir`

There are a few other crates showing up as being deleted, but those are just git being unable to recognize them as renames.

author: khiemngo
body:
Hi @JoshLind , could you please give me some initial feedback on the structured logging (e.g., log entry and event naming, what to log, etc.) when you have time? Thank you! 

PS: I did also take a look at state-sync-v1 and state-sync-v2 logging to learn if there is any naming convention to follow and what to include in a log entry. I was also thinking about logging more data (e.g., peer score after being updated, storage and data client configs) but I'm not quite sure if it is very helpful at the moment.

author: khiemngo
body:
> Thanks @khiemngo! Great start 🚀
> 
> There's a few other things I'd like us to log:
> 
> 1. Each request/response type along with the peer (at `debug` level). We might be able to get away with logging the request data as well (if it's small), but we probably shouldn't log all the response data (because it might be huge).
> 2. Any errors that occur in the rest of the diem data client. These are important to know about.
> 3. When a peer is ignored (i.e., the score drops below the threshold) and when an ignored peer is no longer ignored (i.e., the score rises above the threshold).
> 
> I can provide pointers for these, but I'd like to leave it as an exercise for the reader (so you can get some familiarity with the code) 😄 Let me know if you get blocked!

Thanks for the feedback @JoshLind and @gregnazario . I've tried to add more logging based on the suggestions from you two. I've decided to implement overriding `Debug` for `GlobalDataSummary` (and perhaps also for some other response types) in the next PR. Please let me know if I should make further changes. Thank you!

author: khiemngo
body:
> Thanks @khiemngo! Various comments (mostly nits), but it looks great! Once you address them, this should be good to go! 🚀

Thanks @JoshLind for additional feedback. I addressed all nits. If there are more nits to address, please let me know. Thank you!!

author: bors-libra
body:
Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |

author: CapCap
body: What's the motivation for moving from hashmap to btreemap?

author: JoshLind
body:
@bmwill, is there any context around this? IMO, a change like this should have a well defined reason (and potentially a broader discussion). Not against the idea, but there's a couple open questions in my mind, e.g.:
- What's the main motivation behind this, e.g., issues that stem from the move side or is this one of the concerns of the new decoupled execution projects in consensus?
- If undesired non-determinism is a problem, should we not also be searching out other sources in the codebase (e.g., `rand`)? How far do we want to go?
- What do we lose (if anything) by removing HashMap/Set and replacing them with the BTree equivalents?

author: bmwill
body: I should have left this in Draft form. This is just a POC based on a discussed that was had over how to try and eliminate sources of non-determinism (one of which is iteration over a HashMap). BTree types don't have this issue since items are stored in sorted order.

author: sblackshear
body:
> If undesired non-determinism is a problem, should we not also be searching out other sources in the codebase (e.g., rand)? How far do we want to go?

I think we should go as far as we reasonably can in eliminating or mitigating sources of nondeterminism. It's hard to test for, makes debugging difficult, causes CI issues, and (most importantly) might break consensus safety guarantees if the nondeterminism is in the wrong place.

I think replacing `HashMap`/`Set` with `BTree` variants or (if the perf requirements of `HashMap` are needed or the key type is not `Ord` + can't easily be made `Ord`) using a wrapper that hides some or all iteration API's can go a long way toward getting rid of a common source of nondet behavior. 

Looking at `rand` and other sources of nondeterminism (e.g. file and network interaction) definitely also makes sense, but I think these are (unfortunately) harder to tame and (fortunately) less likely to expose nondeterminism visible to the outside world in my experience.

author: phlip9
metajack
body:
I think perhaps in the same way Rust made RNGs crypto-safe by default, they perhaps should have made other parts of the system deterministic by default allowing people to opt into non-determinism specifically. I suspect the reason they did not is that a) they'd lose most benchmarks and be considered slow, which they nearly did anyway based on their choices around RNGs and b) they probably didn't think non-determinism was that important.

Controlling non-determinism leads to awesome things, such as record/replay testing and ability to have re-execution as a failure handling strategy. It is very hard to retrofit determinism later.

This seems like a big change worthy of some discussion, but I'm generally supportive. I'm curious if there is a noticeable affect on cluster test times?

author: modocache
body: I'd like to review this, but to do so properly I think I'd need to learn more about what block metadata transactions are, and the motivation for providing expiration time in an argument. Is there a link to a description of the work being done here, or could you explain it to me here (or in the commit messages)?

author: vgao1996
body:
@modocache Thanks for helping! I'm not ware of existing docs explaining this concept well so I'll say it in my own words. 
- In the real world, Diem transactions are grouped into "blocks" before getting executed.
- A special transaction, called the "block metadata transaction" or ("block prologue") is inserted at the beginning of every block.
- This transaction updates some of the on-chain metadata, including a global clock. This is how transactions gain access of the concept of "time" during execution.
- The block metadata transaction must be proposed by a validator (the one leading consensus?).
- Transactional tests are a simplified/idealized simulation of the real workflow, so we need to support block metadata transactions.
- There isn't really a concept of "blocks" in transactional tests, so instead we just let the user initiate it whenever they want.

author: tzakian
body:
From the looks of it, the source hash of the move stdlib is changing, which is causing the "git up-to-date" checks for the DPN and experimental frameworks to fail -- so you need to regenerate those artifacts. You can do this by running 

```
cargo run
```
and 
```
cargo run --package experimental
```

in `diem-move/diem-framework`

author: tzakian
body:
You may need to add an additional `--` in front, i.e., something like:
```
cargo run -- --package experimental
```

You should see some regenerated files under `experimental` as well with it. If not let me know and I can dig into it

author: sblackshear
body:
Looks very cool!

> Implement representation of macros in compiled, persisted modules.

Could you say more about how this will work?

> We need to be able to fetch the macro definition from an imported, precompiled module.

I'm wondering why this is a requirement. Macros feel most natural as a source language-only feature to me, and there is some precedent for this with (e.g.) specifications.

author: wrwg
body:
> Looks very cool!
> 
> > Implement representation of macros in compiled, persisted modules.
> 
> Could you say more about how this will work?
> 
> > We need to be able to fetch the macro definition from an imported, precompiled module.
> 
> I'm wondering why this is a requirement. Macros feel most natural as a source language-only feature to me, and there is some precedent for this with (e.g.) specifications.

This is not about the bytecode, but about a representation of modules from other packages we are using since a while containing bytecode + source related metadata. The prover doesn't use that yet (it compiles all transitive sources), but move-lang does.

author: sblackshear
body:
> This is not about the bytecode, but about a representation of modules from other packages we are using since a while containing bytecode + source related metadata. The prover doesn't use that yet (it compiles all transitive sources), but move-lang does.

Got it--that makes sense. I'm glad we get to design this concept of cross-package deps that exist at the source level, but not the bytecode level with two compelling, but slightly different use-cases in mind (specs + macros).

author: sherry-x
body: Is there a health check endpoint for this API?

author: xli
body:
> Is there a health check endpoint for this API?

Use "GET /" for health check unless you need a complex health check like verifying ledger info timestamp. We probably port same function in json-rpc health check logic to new rest api endpoint later.
But in current plan, I will first enable rest api at json-rpc web server first, thus we don't need enable new rest api port in production yet, and use json-rpc web server as entry point of REST API

author: JoshLind
body:
> we probably should add the build in ci, I thought smoke test builds the operational tool?

Yeah, I suspect there's probably a number of crates that are also untested in terms of actually building as stand alone binaries. A test script to build these would probably suffice. The smoke tests don't build the tool as a binary -- they simply invoke it as a library.

author: vgao1996
body:
I think this is a great topic to discuss! I think what you said could be broken down into two separate yet related questions:
1. Whether we want to allow the VM to accept references from the outside, and if so, how?
2. Whether we want to decouple the VM from BCS, and if so, how?

(Having a busy day, so I'll post the rest of my opinions at a later time...)

author: sblackshear
body: To be clear, I don't need (2) for what I have in mind. I definitely think making the VM parametric in a serialization format is useful to think about for the future, but not needed here.

author: vgao1996
body:
Regarding (1), @sblackshear it would be great if you could share a more detailed description of your uses, so that we can better understand what's really driving this and make the right choice.

Without the additional context, here are a few potential solutions folks have so far come up with. For each of them, let's see if it solves your problem and how hard it would be to implement it. Feel feel to correct me if my summary isn't correct or I end up missing something.

## If we only need to support immutable references
Then we can simply allow the VM to initialize a dangling reference using a deserialized value, similar to what we've done with the `&signer`.

## If we need to support mutable references
### Sol 1: Let the VM take a bootstrap stack and return that stack when it finishes execution. 
The tricky part about this, is how you can create the reference arguments and pass them to the function. Our current implementation may be able to workaround the issue since it represents references as `Rc`s, but this is an implementation detail I'm not feeling particularly comfortable exposing. 

Maybe we can have the following API?
```
enum Argument {
    SerializedValue(Vec<u8>),
    Ref(usize),
    MutRef(usize),
}

fn execute_function(
    &mut self,
    bootstrap_stack: Vec<Vec<u8>>,
    args: Vec<Argument>,
    ...
) -> VMResult<Vec<Vec<u8>>>; // returning the bootstrap stack
```

### Sol 2: Exploit the global storage by implementing a special adapter
The special adapter would have two different "regions" in its memory space:
1. Your usual global storage, backed up by a real database
2. Some special values under some special addresses which gets inserted by the adapter before a transaction gets executed. These values are stored in memory.

After a transaction finishes, side effects to these "virtual global values" will be included in the ChangeSet.

Pro: this doesn't have to change anything in the Move VM. The Move VM wouldn't even notice anything special.
Con: bad ergonomics + general complexity.

### Sol 3: Events
Could you pass in some of these mutable references in owned forms, and then emit the side effects as events?

author: sblackshear
body:
- I have edited my original post to add some additional context on the use-case.
- I do indeed need to simulate both immutable and mutable references into my special store
- I think (1) sounds like the best option. (2) has some UX issues I'd prefer not to deal with (e.g., user entrypoints will have to know where to look up these special values), and I'm concerned about the cost of putting the special values in global storage as well. I'm actually doing something along the lines of (2) right now, but it's so hacky I don't even want to describe it :). (3) also has UX issues: I want refs to these values to look like ordinary Move references instead of requiring users to write one set of logic for handling refs to the special store and another to handle normal refs.

Let me summarize my understanding of how `execution_function` should work (and let me know if I got it wrong):
- Everything in `bootstrap_stack` gets `StoreLoc`'d to create a stack frame. Let's call this "the bootstrap stack frame".
- `args` is evaluated against the locals in the bootstrap stack frame to create a vec of `MoveValueImpl`'s. These then get passed into the function specified in the `...`'s. Any sensible `args` will create a reference to each value in `bootstrap_stack`--otherwise, it contains a redundant value somewhere.
- After execution of the function concludes, the caller gets back the final values of the locals from `bootstrap_stack` (which may have been mutated via the references created by processing `args1).
- The caller also gets back the side effects from executing the function (e.g., events, change set) in `mut self`.

author: vgao1996
body:
Yeah, I think your understanding of `execution_function` is correct. Just to be clear that if we do end up implementing this, we'll likely just create the bootstrap stack via some internal VM logic instead of executing the actual `StoreLoc` instructions.

I now feel a lot better about this approach after writing it down and I can see how it is conceptually similar to (2), but in a "more cleanly separated and strongly typed" manner. I'd be happy to discuss this further if you are interested! More specifically, I think we need to figure out
- Is the bootstrap stack the best representation for this type of "memory region"? Could there be better alternatives?
- How can we initialize the references in a safe manner? Would the one I wrote above work?

@tnowacki, I know you also have opinions on this. Any thoughts?

author: tnowacki
body:
I think everything for references is relatively straightforward. You have some additional frame outside before executing, everything else is a bit of an implementation detail. (Though getting the API right for viewing things afterwards might be a bit tricky, but I don't think we need to sort that out just yet). So I think we can/should do it. And we can sort out the details on the PR that does it, no need to get into the weeds here. 

My bigger concern is with doing this for  arbitrary types.

---
Background: 
- I am currently worried actually that we let the VM call private functions with `execute_function`. I worry this sort of violates the module's rules though it is up to an adapter to violate those rules... 
- More importantly, I worry about violating any sort of guarantees around structs/resources. A module should have tight control on the creation of struct values. Again, I know this is an adapter thing and adapters can already violate all sorts of things
- I think any sort of possible violations here makes things harder for the prover (you could just mint things willynilly at the adapter level, for example) (though this is already the case in that writesets could do this)

With that bit of background, here are some spots I'm thinking about  
- At some point we want private types.
- Similarly, I think at some point we want to add public constructors.
- MUCH MORE SPECULATIVE. We might want some way of a specifying a function to initialize arg values for a move script (solving this string problem)
- Could we limit `execute_function` to just this API. That is the same API we will have for scripts?
- If we view `execute_function` as basically being a "writeset-like" API, we might not care. In that case, should we make sure that the values in `execute_function` at least have `drop` since they aren't really going anywhere?

author: wrwg
tnowacki
body:
@wrwg, I like the idea of marking what functions can or cannot be invoked by `execute_function`

> I wish we just had package visibility, that would simplify Move usage

I have started to have some similar thoughts. `public(friend)` was added at a time when our whole package story was a lot less defined, it was sort of an overly general solution in the absence of a well defined package system. 

Could you explain a bit more about what you would want from "package visibility"? I am thinking the compiler could maybe just add this as a source level feature, (depending on what it is you envision)

author: wrwg
wrwg
body:
> > I wish we just had package visibility, that would simplify Move usage
> 
> I have started to have some similar thoughts. `public(friend)` was added at a time when our whole package story was a lot less defined, it was sort of an overly general solution in the absence of a well defined package system.
> 
> Could you explain a bit more about what you would want from "package visibility"? I am thinking the compiler could maybe just add this as a source level feature, (depending on what it is you envision)

If the compiler would support the "package" visibility, then that's equivalent to making those functions friends, and declare all other modules in the package as friends of the given module. When we designed the friend mechanism, we knew it could be used as a lower-level mechanism for something like this.

Why would we do this? Added convenience, no need for the friend module declarations. Less divergence of Move from other languages, so less confusion. And it would be totally adequate for what we need "friends" for in the prover.

author: msmouse
body: Curious why this is useful?

author: zihaoccc
body:
> Curious why this is useful?

I reckon this option can have full log instead of truncated? I only have one concern, if we make this as default, will it cause any issue if log is too much by always appending at the end? shall we make it optional?

author: JoshLind
body:
Thanks, all 😄

> Curious why this is useful?

@msmouse, this is helpful if a node crashes and then reboots, so it doesn't overwrite the old node log and just starts appending to it. One concrete example is a smoke test that starts a node, stops it, does some stuff and then brings it up again to verify state sync or consensus. In this situation, it's useful to be able to track the old log and new log after the restart.

> I only have one concern, if we make this as default, will it cause any issue if log is too much by always appending at the end? shall we make it optional?

I'm not really concerned about this. Logs can already grow too large today (e.g., if the node stays online for too long). So, operators need to be watching this anyway. Overwriting the old log is worse (in my opinion), because it impairs debugging.

/land

author: bors-libra
body:
:exclamation: Invalid command
Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |

author: xli
body:
> This is a great start, but there's obviously a few issues:
> 
> * The code won't compile because a fully qualified Move module name like `01::M::S1<u64>` is not a valid Rust identifier.
> * The generator can only generate code for closed types, so we'll end up creating a struct definition for each specialization of a generic type. From looking at serde `Format` and `ContainerFormat` I don't _think_ we can do any better than this (they require closed types), but I could be wrong.
> * We generate definitions for Move ground types like `AccountAddress`, but it might be nice for those to live elsewhere
> * It might be nice to group generated struct definitions into a namespace per address and/or per module
> 
> Curious to hear thoughts on which of these are addressable/how we should tackle it.

I think we may consider:
1. module name => file name
2. account address (0x1) => a directory name by specifying additional cli arguments

So we probably can generate yaml files into a target directory instead of one file.

As not all languages support generic type, so closed types probably easier for generating code in more languages.

We have AccountAddress generated already as diem core types, so we probably need a cli argument to specify where is known types package and module and use them instead of generating them, I think current transaction builder cli has the option to do so for using diem core types (includes AccountAddress) when generating stdlib functions.

author: bob-wilson
body: I think this needs more discussion. In particular, for single NFTs you lose a lot of flexibility by having separate TokenData, especially if that data remains in the creator's account. If you want a NFT's properties to change over time, e.g., based on what the owner does with it, I think it is better to have a self-contained resource.

author: zekun000
bob-wilson
body:
> @bob-wilson we're trying to unify the multi token and single token resource for consistency

Yes, I know and I am questioning whether to do that unification. If people are creating static NFTs and want a single interface, they can choose to use the multi-token module regardless of the count. But, if people want dynamic NFTs, the multi-token interface doesn't seem like it would work and I think it will be important for us to support some kind of self-contained single-token NFTs.

author: zekun000
body:
yeah, i don't have strong opinion on whether we should unify or not. another alternative is to have optional token data in the MultiToken's Token struct, but I found that introduces more complexity.

anyway, @dmitri-perelman brought this up during the hackathon, maybe he can chime in.

author: dmitri-perelman
body:
@bob-wilson why do you think that the mutability of NFT is related to the inlining of the token data? (I thought that it was orthogonal, but I might have missed something). My gut feeling was to enable inlining of TokenData via the optional field, but @zekun000 believes it introduces complexity.
We could get to a place with MutableNFT being a separate struct, but the main motivation for unifying these was to help the users of these structs (wallets / exchanges / etc.) to avoid duplication of functionality for different NFT types.

author: bob-wilson
body: From the document that @emmazzz wrote earlier, it looks to me like the non-inline TokenData resource remains in the creator's account. I guess I was assuming that the owner of the NFT may not have access to modify the resource in the creator's account. I think there are a variety of reasons why it may be desirable for an NFT to be self-contained. What if I want to sell an NFT to someone on a different blockchain? How can that work if the TokenData stays on the account where it was created?

author: zekun000
body:
having the optional field doesn't seem able to help avoid duplication of functionality of two nft types though. users have to check the optional data and supply to tell whether it's non-fungible or semi-fungible. in that sense, two structs seems cleaner with clear separation.

by complexity I think it blurs the property of the data, imagine whether the token data is copyable or not. for inline usecase, the data has to be copyable but for separate storage or single token, the data has to be unique.

author: dmitri-perelman
body:
> I think there are a variety of reasons why it may be desirable for an NFT to be self-contained. What if I want to sell an NFT to someone on a different blockchain?

Specifically for x-chain purchases, inlining seems less important (another blockchain would have to figure out a way to create a compatible struct while a given balance would be burned in our blockchain).
But in general I definitely support inlining for single-tokened NFTs (being separate struct or a unified struct)

author: dmitri-perelman
body:
> having the optional field doesn't seem able to help avoid duplication of functionality of two nft types though. users have to check the optional data and supply to tell whether it's non-fungible or semi-fungible.

The use case I had in mind was building a wallet that can hold / sell the NFTs (which would benefit from a single `transfer` function provided by the NFT).
Again, no strong opinions here!

author: dmitri-perelman
body:
> for inline usecase, the data has to be copyable but for separate storage or single token, the data has to be unique.

Btw, why do you think the data should be copyable in that case? I imagined it'd be moved around together with the ownership.

author: zekun000
body:
> Btw, why do you think the data should be copyable in that case?

I thought we'd allow the multi token to inline the data as well, in that case, the split function needs to duplicate the inline data.

author: emmazzz
body: Regarding mutable NFTs, right now we have been concerned with only immutable NFTs. Both the NFT and MultiToken modules don't allow the token data to be modified, whether it is inlined in the token itself or not. I do think we need to have a separate discussion about mutable NFTs when the time comes. Even mutable NFTs maybe have some data that's immutable (e.g., date of birth, artist name). We need to design the MutableNFT module carefully so that only the data we want to allow mutating can be mutated, and other immutable metadata is guaranteed to stay the same.

author: bors-libra
body:
:exclamation: Invalid command
Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |

author: tzakian
body:
After some offline discussion the current plan to resolve this issue is to make it an error if you have modules/scripts that would cause issues on a case-insensitive filesystem (regardless of the file system you're currently on). While a bit restrictive we feel this is fine since:
* The solution is relatively straightforward and we can provide a good error message/help on what to do
* It maximizes reusability of Move packages by other people (e.g., someone develops a package that works on their Linux machine, but then I can't use their package on my Mac machine).

:exclamation: Invalid command
Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |

author: sblackshear
body:
Like this approach--very clean for how generic it is!

Couple of high-level questions:
- Is the idea here to compile from Move source code to EVM bytecode, Move bytecode to EVM bytecode, or Move source to Solidity? I assume the first one because of the annotations, but wanted to make sure I understand (and could also see value in the other two approaches).
- If I compile the Move code examples here to Move bytecode and run them on the Move VM, then compile/run the same code on the EVM, what are the guarantees you are trying to provide (if any) about behavioral equivalence between the Move execution trace and the EVM execution trace? I can guess the answer includes something about the equivalence of changes to the Move and EVM global states, but the story on errors/gas in each trace is less clear to me.

author: wrwg
body:
> Like this approach--very clean for how generic it is!
> 
> Couple of high-level questions:
> 
> * Is the idea here to compile from Move source code to EVM bytecode, Move bytecode to EVM bytecode, or Move source to Solidity? I assume the first one because of the annotations, but wanted to make sure I understand (and could also see value in the other two approaches).

In the first prototype, I plan to generate Solidity from the prover's stackless bytecode. Eventually, this should be a bytecode-to-bytecode transformation. We would need to access the attributes somehow for this.

> * If I compile the Move code examples here to Move bytecode and run them on the Move VM, then compile/run the same code on the EVM, what are the guarantees you are trying to provide (if any) about behavioral equivalence between the Move execution trace and the EVM execution trace? I can guess the answer includes something about the equivalence of changes to the Move and EVM global states, but the story on errors/gas in each trace is less clear to me.

Good questions. Since a "contract", which can consist of many modules, has its own private Move address space, the execution semantics would be different, but it could/should be made as compatible as possible. For gas, we would need to adopt to EVM. For error treatment (e.g. arithmetics) we should preserve the Move semantics by generating according code. In general, it would be crucial that we preserve as much as we can the "safety" aspects of Move, otherwise why would one want to use Move on EVM? How that looks like in detail has to be figured out.

author: sblackshear
body:
Thanks, that helps a lot!

Variant of the second question: would you expect users to write tests in Move or in Solidity, and would the test runner execute Move or EVM bytecode?

author: wrwg
body:
> Thanks, that helps a lot!
> 
> Variant of the second question: would you expect users to write tests in Move or in Solidity, and would the test runner execute Move or EVM bytecode?

Very good question. Executing Move within one EVM contract, and without cross-contract calls, should have the same semantics as the Move VM. So yes, Move unit tests should be applicable for the majority of the Move code,

If it comes to cross-contract calls, all bets are open.

author: wrwg
body:
Can you please hold back with this until we had a chance to discuss in person. FWIW, I have a pending change for sets as well, but figured they make little sense until we have contains (predicate based)/filter/map (henceforth the macro/combinators proposal).

Also, anything based on BCS is not only poison for the prover, but also any other form of symbolic analysis.

Moreover, if we introduce sets or maps, we should not put the way how they are implemented into the name of the data structure. Move is not C++ or Rust. We already support universal equality on any, even generic values, which none of those languages do. We can have `Set` and `Map` based semantically on equality. Whether the implementation uses BCS or whatever is an implementation detail. I'm worried if we put `BCS` in the name we soon will expose functionality which only works if the impl is actually also based on `BCS`, which is an unnecessary detail, killing the ability for symbolic reasoning without any practical need. For the record, Solidity also has just "maps" and not "hash_map" or similar.

author: sblackshear
body:
> Can you please hold back with this until we had a chance to discuss 

No worries, this is an RFC (and thank you for the C's, good start to the discussion!) But I thought it was important to get a concrete proposal out (even if flawed) since this feature has been requested/discussed many times without progress.

> FWIW, I have a pending change for sets as well

Looking forward to seeing it!

> predicate based)/filter/map (henceforth the macro/combinators proposal).

Supporting predicates for all of our collections seems essential. Since we have ideas on how to support these predicates for vectors and this set is backed by a vector, I don't see any barriers to supporting these operations for sets using the vector ones.

> Also, anything based on BCS is not only poison for the prover, but also any other form of symbolic analysis.

This is a challenge, as noted in the PR summary. FWIW, I think analyses (including the prover) could fairly easily be extended to reason about sets of types with a natural order (e.g., `u64`) or wrappers of those types, but reasoning about the BCS encoding of arbitrary types seems quite hard.

> Moreover, if we introduce sets or maps, we should not put the way how they are implemented into the name of the data structure... Whether the implementation uses BCS or whatever is an implementation detail.

The `BCS` in the name is intended to make programmers think about the ordering they are going to get if they iterate over the set. Because iteration is supported, the fact that it uses BCS is not an implementation detail.

> We can have Set and Map based semantically on equality

This is also a valid approach with its own pros and cons. My main concern with this is expressivity of iteration. If you want to put things in a set or map and iterate over them in order, you can't do that with the equality-based approach--the only iteration strategy you can support is iteration order. 

It probably makes sense to have both kinds of collections and ban iteration for equality-based collections (or be very careful to emphasize that you get insertion order rather than anything semantic).

There's also some interesting questions about efficiency--equality-based collections are likely much more efficient for smaller collection sizes, but once they get big enough the binary search of the BCS-based approach will buy you something. Worth nothing that all collections in Move code I've seen today are very small.

Also curious to hear your thoughts on the `ord`-based strategy mentioned in the PR summary vs equality-based collections.

author: tnowacki
body:
> This is also a valid approach with its own pros and cons. My main concern with this is expressivity of iteration. If you want to put things in a set or map and iterate over them in order, you can't do that with the equality-based approach--the only iteration strategy you can support is iteration order.

Since we already have equality in the language, and don't have general ordering, I think it might be a bit easier to add insertion-ordered sets/maps as the first type for sets/maps.

I'm a bit skeptical around things like `ord` as it a gets a bit funky as you cannot define your own ordering. That somehow bothers me less than byte-based equality.

> > This is also a valid approach with its own pros and cons. My main concern with this is expressivity of iteration. If you want to put things in a set or map and iterate over them in order, you can't do that with the equality-based approach--the only iteration strategy you can support is iteration order.
> 
> Since we already have equality in the language, and don't have general ordering, I think it might be a bit easier to add insertion-ordered sets/maps as the first type for sets/maps.
> 
> I'm a bit skeptical around things like `ord` as it a gets a bit funky as you cannot define your own ordering. That somehow bothers me less than byte-based equality.

Totally a fan of insertion order for this problem.

author: wrwg
body:
> > > This is also a valid approach with its own pros and cons. My main concern with this is expressivity of iteration. If you want to put things in a set or map and iterate over them in order, you can't do that with the equality-based approach--the only iteration strategy you can support is iteration order.
> > 
> > 
> > Since we already have equality in the language, and don't have general ordering, I think it might be a bit easier to add insertion-ordered sets/maps as the first type for sets/maps.
> > I'm a bit skeptical around things like `ord` as it a gets a bit funky as you cannot define your own ordering. That somehow bothers me less than byte-based equality.
> 
> Totally a fan of insertion order for this problem.

To follow up on this, BCS based keying is for symbolic reasoning the end of the world. Ord is just a bit better, in that the world goes on but turns into an endless nightmare ;-) 

We already spent a lot of time into getting equality somehow working, as it is not natively supported for aggregate types in SMT solvers. With Ord the same set of problems we had with equality returns  scaled up by one order of magnitude. Because we need to reason about order of iteration, both BCS and Ord will disallow us to deal with the problem by using uninterpreted functions with axiomatized properties, as we do today with BCS and Hash. We would need to precisely model BCS/ord as it is done in the language.

Insertion order is the best way to go from symbolic reasoning (prover) perspective. I understand that it may cause some overhead, but Java's LinkedHashMap implementation e.g. shows that it can still be done efficiently (probably natively) using hashing for lookup and update.

In general I think we should consider sets/maps etc. to be relative small (tables are the large things) so the overhead should be OK.
