author: bmwill
body:
While you can use features this way it's generally discouraged because you'd need a feature flag for each length and then the features are no longer additive. 

I wonder if a more scalable solution would be to use const generics to determine the size of the address.

author: lxfind
body:
> I wonder if a more scalable solution would be to use const generics to determine the size of the address.

Would love to make this more generic. Thought about const generics, but couldn't see a way to do this without changing everything (all uses of AccountAddress and classes that have it). Would love to hear ideas on how to do this!
I could use a build.rs to generate the length definition based on a config, if that works for the team.

author: wrwg
body:
> > I wonder if a more scalable solution would be to use const generics to determine the size of the address.
> 
> Would love to make this more generic. Thought about const generics, but couldn't see a way to do this without changing everything (all uses of AccountAddress and classes that have it). Would love to hear ideas on how to do this! I could use a build.rs to generate the length definition based on a config, if that works for the team.

I think any technique, let it be generated build.rs or generic const or like done here, will lead to that there are two exclusive flavors of the Move binaries. The only way out of this seems to me dynamically sized addresses, which has performance and other far reaching implications, so I guess I'm good with this one here.

author: tnowacki
body:
> I could use a build.rs to generate the length definition based on a config, if that works for the team.

Could you show more what that would look like? Even a mock up of some sorts is fine for now.

Just not entirely sure what goes in the `build.rs`

author: lxfind
body:
Turns out that I don't have to use build.rs (I was initially thinking about having build.rs generating a rs file that contains a definition of LENGTH based on an environment variable).
I discovered a crate called "const_env", which allows you to declare a const integer from an environment variable.
Updated the change. Now we could specify the address length through environment variable ADDRESS_LENGTH. It's default to 16.

author: wrwg
body:
> Turns out that I don't have to use build.rs (I was initially thinking about having build.rs generating a rs file that contains a definition of LENGTH based on an environment variable). I discovered a crate called "const_env", which allows you to declare a const integer from an environment variable. Updated the change. Now we could specify the address length through environment variable ADDRESS_LENGTH. It's default to 16.

I think this just makes it worse compared to the exclusive cfg feature you have used before. const_env evaluates environment variables at compile time. Thus compilation of the Move code now depends magically on some environment variable, which is less transparent than the cargo feature, but comes exactly with the same disadvantages which are [listed for exclusive features here](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/reference/features.html#mutually-exclusive-features).

With the feature, one can at least specify in the toml on which flavor of Move one wants to depend. With the environment variable, it is even not possible to request an address flavor via a dependency.  

While exclusive features are discouraged in general,  there are cases (like this here) where they are needed. Lets use a feature instead of some obscure dependency on an env variable at compile time. As I said, the only way to do this better than with features is via dynamic (at runtime) configurable address length, but this is to big of a refactoring.

author: tnowacki
body:
I'd still like to better understand how the build.rs solution would work, but I agree with @wrwg that the env based approach is much much worse. 

build.rs aside. Could we at least make the cfg feature based solution cleaner?
I think in the previous iteration, @lxfind, you had conditionally declared the constant depending on the feature. While functionally equivalent, could we do something like `const C: u64 = if cfg!(feature = "my_cool_addr_length_feature") { 0 } else { 1 };` instead?

author: lxfind
body:
> I'd still like to better understand how the build.rs solution would work, but I agree with @wrwg that the env based approach is much much worse.
> 
> build.rs aside. Could we at least make the cfg feature based solution cleaner? I think in the previous iteration, @lxfind, you had conditionally declared the constant depending on the feature. While functionally equivalent, could we do something like `const C: u64 = if cfg!(feature = "my_cool_addr_length_feature") { 0 } else { 1 };` instead?

Thanks for the feedback! @wrwg @tnowacki 
The approach with build.rs will only be worse in this regard (I was planning to generate a rust file that contains the definition of LENGTH based on environment variables and include it in account_address. So I won't go that route.

The closest I can do with if/else would be something like this:
```
pub const LENGTH: usize = match () {
        #[cfg(feature = "address20")]
        () => 20,
        #[cfg(not(feature = "address20"))]
        () => 16,
    };
```
which isn't much better than
```
#[cfg(feature = "address20")]
pub const LENGTH: usize = 20;
#[cfg(not(feature = "address20"))]
pub const LENGTH: usize = 16;
```

author: msmouse
body:
This fixes a Fuzzing failure introduced in 1.5. We'd like this fix to go in so that our fuzzing environment can be deployed for 1.5.

I downloaded the corpus in production environment and reproduced the breakage locally. Then with this fix it didn't break soon after the start of running like before, although it failed with another target (fix needed from the VM team).

I also added a proptest to do the same thing as the fuzzer, although it's hard to trigger in an unittest environment, but it's an effort to hopefully make the unittests flaky on a similar break in the future so we see signals before fuzzing is deployed. The proptest (#9669) is not picked, to minimize the pick.

author: wrwg
body:
> That the write back is deferred is by design. In fact a Move program would not be able to observe updates until they are written back. I would tend to keep it like this and consider the inline spec (a rarely used feature) to be invalid. Are there more implications which I'm missing?

We could though write back earlier however I wonder how complete would this be anyway? What happens if we have an inlined spec block which tries to access a &mut which is still alive after the code block? It appears if we fix this just for the lucky case where the &mut goes out of scope before the spec block, we may have some subtle effects if this is changed, so perhaps it is cleaner to just not support this (and perhaps even produce an error message).

author: meng-xu-cs
meng-xu-cs
body:
The main point of this PR though, is not to address the rarely used case of the inline spec, but to address the issue where a reference value that is only defined in one path is considered live from the beginning of the function:

Following is the live_var analysis result of the test case under `move-prover/bytecode/tests/livevar_after_memory_instr` *before* this PR (had the test case existed): and the weiredness is marked with `===>` in corresponding lines:

```

     var $t3|x: &mut u64

     var $t5: &mut Test::Inner
     var $t6: u64
     var $t7: bool
     var $t8: bool
     var $t9: bool
     var $t10: bool
     # live vars: cond, s, $t4, $t5  ===> NOTE: $t4, $t5 are marked live from the beginning of the function
  0: if ($t0) goto 35 else goto 38
     # live vars: s, $t4
  1: label L1
     # live vars: s, $t4
  2: goto 7
     # live vars: s, $t5
  3: label L0
     # live vars: s, $t5
  4: $t4 := borrow_field<Test::Outer>.f1($t1) ===> but $t4 is only defined here
     # live vars: s, $t4, $t5
  5: $t2 := Test::ret_mut_inner($t4)
     # live vars: s, tmp#$2, $t4, $t5
  6: goto 10
     # live vars: s, $t4
  7: label L2
     # live vars: s, $t4
  8: $t5 := borrow_field<Test::Outer>.f2($t1)  ===> and $t5 is only defined here
     # live vars: s, $t4, $t5

     # live vars: s, tmp#$2, $t4, $t5

     # live vars: s, $t4, $t5

     # live vars: s, $t4, $t5
 23: $t9 := is_parent[Reference($t1).f1]($t4) ===> $t4 is considered live here although it is defined on only one code path that reaches this point
     # live vars: s, $t4, $t5, $t9

author: bors-libra
body:
Bors help and documentation
Bors is a Github App used to manage merging of PRs in order to ensure that CI is always green. It does so by maintaining a [Merge Queue](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). Once a PR reaches the head of the Merge Queue it is rebased on top of the latest version of the PR's `base-branch` (generally `master`) and then triggers CI. If CI comes back green the PR is then merged into the `base-branch`. Regardless of the outcome, the next PR is the queue is then processed. ### General - This project's Merge Queue can be found [here](https://github.com/diem/diem/projects/2). - This project requires PRs to be [Reviewed](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-reviews) and Approved before they can be queued for merging. - Before PR's can be merged they must be configured with ["Allow edits from maintainers"](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) enabled. This is needed for Bors to be able to update PR's in-place so that Github can properly recognize and mark them as "merged" once they've been merged into the upstream branch. ### Commands Bors actions can be triggered by posting a comment which includes a line of the form `/`. | Command | Action | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | __Land__ | `land`, `merge` | attempt to land or merge a PR | | __Canary__ | `canary`, `try` | canary a PR by performing all checks without merging | | __Cancel__ | `cancel`, `stop` | stop an in-progress land | | __Cherry Pick__ | `cherry-pick ` | cherry-pick a PR into `` branch | | __Priority__ | `priority` | set the priority level for a PR (`high`, `normal`, `low`) | | __Help__ | `help`, `h` | show this help message | ### Options Options for Pull Requests are configured through the application of labels. |           Option           | Description | | --- | --- | | ![label: bors-high-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-high-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is high-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the head of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-low-priority](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-low-priority&color=lightgrey) | Indicates that the PR is low-priority. When queued the PR will be placed at the back of the merge queue. | | ![label: bors-squash](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=&message=bors-squash&color=lightgrey) | Before merging the PR will be squashed down to a single commit, only retaining the commit message of the first commit in the PR. |
